Written evidence submitted by the Legal Action Group (LAG) (LAI 0025)default&#xa0;
defaultCivil defaultLegal Aid- the Secret defaultLegal defaultService?default&#xa0;
defaultLAG has found a disturbing reduction in the take-up of legal aid cases in civil law for the first quarte
defaultr of the current year, 2013/14.
default&#xa0;
defaultThe Legal Aid Sentencing and Punishment of Offenders (LASPO) Act 
defaultintroduced sweeping cuts to scope in legal aid from April this year. What LAG’s research shows is that for the cases which are still covered by legal aid there has been a large reduction in the take-up of legal aid services for these by public. We believe 
defaultthis has been caused by
default a combination of factors
default 
defaultincluding, 
defaultthe reduction
default 
defaultin the number of solicitors firms and charities, such as Citizens Advice Bureaux, offering legal aid
default, a perception amongst the
default 
defaultpublic 
defaultthat
default 
defaultthey can
default no
default-longer
default 
defaultget help with any civil law problems 
defaultand 
defaultthe failure by the government to adequately advertise the availability of services.
default&#xa0;
defaultDownward Trend in Casesdefault&#xa0;
defaultPrevious figures released by LAG show that the number of civil legal aid cases has been in decline over t
defaulthe last few years. It is in the social welfare law (SWL) category that the biggest falls have occurred. From just under half a million cases at their peak in 2009-10 the number of SWL cases had dropped to 293,319 last year.
