defaultThe reducing number of SWL cases is surprising given the continuing difficult economic outlook and the numbers of 
defaultcases reaching the courts and tribunals system. For example in the quarter ending 31
defaultst
default Dec 2012 there had been a 48% increase in the number of cases brought to the Social Security and Child Support Tribunal.
default Citizens Advice has also reported increasing nu
defaultmbers of enquiries in the first three quarters of 2012/13. However, in the final quarter Bureaux capacity to deal with specialist cases was reduced as they prepared for the withdrawal of legal aid from much of SWL. 
default We believe the reduction in the numbers
default of cases since 2010 has been caused by changes to the system, such as the reduction in the numbers of cases legal aid firm are permitted to commence, rather than a decrease in the numbers of people needing assistance. 
default&#xa0;
defaultThe trend over the last few years 
defaultha
defaults been of concern, but the
default latest 
defaultfigures 
defaultfor the first quarter of the current year (outlined below) show that the take-up of legal aid services in common areas of 
defaultcivil 
defaultlaw has fallen off a cliff.
