defaultLAG believes that the very large shortfall in discrimination law can be explained by the 100% reduction in the availability of legal aid for employment law cases. 
defaultIn the employment law category 
defaultthe government projected that 78% of cases
default,
default 
defaultout of a total of 24,000, 
defaultwould be taken from scope
default. T
defaulthe remaining 22
default% would be discrimination ones. However, m
defaultost discrimination law cases usually stem from a dispute in the workplace, but as no legal aid is ava
defaultilable for employment law advice people who have been discriminated against are less likely to seek help.
default Another factor in the low take-up of legal aid for discrimination
default,
default 
defaultas well as debt 
defaultcases
default,
default might also be the government’s decision to shift all initial
default enquiries onto 
defaultthe Civil Legal Advice (CLA) service which is an internet and telephone based 
defaultservice
